# Non-secret AGENT_* knobs for local dev. Nothing loads this file automatically — export via
# your shell or direnv; a copied `.env` is gitignored. The config contract is layered
# flags > env (`AGENT_*`) > file (`.agent.toml`) > defaults (see `.rules`); env > defaults is
# what exists today — the flags and `.agent.toml` layers land with the engine-surface phases.
#
# agent holds NO secrets: the engine needs no API key, and tenancy/auth belong to the hoster
# (guardrail 4). If you find yourself adding a credential here, the change is mis-scoped.

# --- Logging ---
# AGENT_LOG=warn                      # error | warn | info | debug | trace (stderr; stdout is the run result)

# --- Boot & exec ---
# AGENT_FIRECRACKER=firecracker       # the firecracker binary — a PATH name or an absolute path
# AGENT_KERNEL=artifacts/vmlinux      # uncompressed ELF/PVH guest kernel (`cargo xtask fetch-artifacts`)
#
# Default rootfs: boots to a console prompt but has no in-guest agent — the `run --demo-boot` path.
# AGENT_ROOTFS=artifacts/rootfs.ext4  # base rootfs; a read-write boot runs against a fresh per-VM copy
# AGENT_MARKER=login:                 # console substring meaning "the guest reached userspace"
#                                     # (tied to this image — change it if you swap the rootfs)
#
# To run code in the guest, point at the built agent rootfs (`cargo xtask build-rootfs`) and its
# readiness marker — the two go together (the marker is the line the agent prints once it's listening):
# AGENT_ROOTFS=artifacts/rootfs-agent.ext4
# AGENT_MARKER=AGENT-GUEST-READY
#   e.g.  AGENT_ROOTFS=artifacts/rootfs-agent.ext4 AGENT_MARKER=AGENT-GUEST-READY \
#           cargo run -p agent-cli -- run -- python3 -c 'print(2 + 2)'
#
# Not env knobs — set in code, deliberately (ARCHITECTURE decisions 004/005/006): the read-only base +
# per-run tmpfs overlay, bulk read-only input via a second block device, and bulk writable output via
# a third (pulled back with `RunningVm::collect_outputs`). Don't hunt for an
# `AGENT_READONLY`/`AGENT_INPUT`/`AGENT_OUTPUT`; they're per-VM boot inputs the caller sets, not
# layered config.
